      <div class="verdict" id="quick-verdict">
        <strong>Quick verdict:</strong> The <strong>BenQ ScreenBar Halo</strong> is the best monitor light bar we have tested. Asymmetric optics eliminate screen glare entirely, the wireless knob is genuinely useful, and the auto-dimming sensor nails brightness in changing light. At $129 it is expensive for a desk light, but if you work at a monitor after dark, nothing else comes close.
      </div>

      <p>For years we tolerated cheap clip-on LED bars that threw half their light straight into the screen and left the desk in shadow. We assumed monitor light bars were a category limited by physics — until BenQ shipped the original ScreenBar in 2017 and proved that asymmetric optics could redirect every photon downward. The Halo, released as the third generation, layers on a wireless knob and an ambient light sensor at $129.</p>

      <p>We ran the Halo on our primary workstation for 90 days, side by side with three competitors: the original BenQ ScreenBar Plus ($99), the Baseus swipe-control bar ($39), and the Yeelight Pro bar ($69). We measured lux at the desk, photographed the screen for reflection, and timed how often we touched the knob in a typical week. Here is what we found.</p>

      <p>If you want the short version: the Halo is the new benchmark, but it is not the right purchase for every desk. Below we break down where it earns its price and where the original ScreenBar Plus is still the smarter call.</p>

      <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Product Summary</h2>
      <ProductSummary pros={pros} cons={cons} bestFor={bestFor} notFor={notFor} />

      <h2 id="who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</h2>
      <p>See the summary above for a quick breakdown of who this product is best for and who should skip it.</p>

      <h2 id="detailed-review">Detailed Review</h2>

      <h3>Light Quality: Asymmetric Optics in Practice</h3>
      <p>The single biggest reason to buy any BenQ ScreenBar is the asymmetric optical design. Rather than firing LED light in a 180-degree hemisphere (which is what every cheap bar does), the Halo uses a custom lens that bends the beam forward and downward at roughly a 25-degree angle. The result is that 100% of the light lands on your desk and keyboard, and zero of it reflects off your monitor.</p>

      <p>We tested this two ways. First, we photographed a glossy 27-inch iMac screen with the Halo on, then with the Baseus bar at the same brightness. The Baseus produced a visible horizontal streak across the top third of the screen; the Halo produced nothing. Second, we measured lux at the keyboard with both bars set to maximum brightness. The Halo delivered 480 lux at the desk surface, while the Baseus managed only 290 lux — because half its output was bouncing off the screen and into the ceiling.</p>

      <p>This is not a marginal improvement. If you have ever squinted through a reflection of your own light bar at night, the Halo fixes it completely. Pair it with a <a href="/reviews/best-monitor-riser-desk/">monitor riser</a> to bring the bar to the right height for your eye line, and the desk-lighting problem is solved for good.</p>

      <h3>The Wireless Knob: Gimmick or Game-Changer?</h3>
      <p>The Halo's headline feature is the wireless control knob. It is a palm-sized aluminum puck that pairs with the bar over Bluetooth and charges magnetically by snapping onto a contact pad on top of the bar itself. You rotate it to change brightness across 15 levels, press to toggle power, and hold for two seconds to disable auto-dimming.</p>

      <p>For the first week we were skeptical. The knob sat on the desk looking like a paperweight. By week two we noticed we were adjusting brightness three or four times per evening without thinking about it — sunset hitting the window, kids turning on the kitchen light, the room getting darker as we worked. The knob made those micro-adjustments trivial, and the auto-dimming handled most of them for us anyway.</p>

      <p>Battery life is real. BenQ claims 40 days per charge, and we measured 37 days with the knob used roughly 8 times per day. Charging takes about 90 minutes from a USB-C phone charger. The knob does not need to be on the bar to function — it just needs to be within Bluetooth range, which is roughly 30 feet in our test space.</p>

      <p>The one flaw: the magnetic attachment is strong enough to hold the knob during charging but weak enough that a careless elbow will send it to the floor. We dropped it twice in three months. It survived both times, but if you have a cluttered desk, the knob can become another thing to lose. If you want a more traditional review of light options without a knob, our <a href="/reviews/best-desk-lamp-eye-care/">desk lamp eye care roundup</a> covers in-line dimmer alternatives.</p>

      <h3>Auto-Dimming Sensor: How Well It Works</h3>
      <p>The Halo has a small ambient light sensor on the front of the bar, just below the LED strip. It reads the lux at the desk every few seconds and adjusts brightness to maintain a target level. In our tests it matched our manual choices in 8 of 10 lighting scenarios. The two failures were both in mixed light — afternoon sun plus a warm lamp — where the sensor read the average and chose a brightness slightly too low for our preference.</p>

      <p>You can disable auto-dimming by holding the knob for two seconds. We left it on for most of the test period and forgot it existed, which is the highest compliment we can pay an ambient sensor. The original ScreenBar Plus has a sensor too, but it only dims — it does not brighten — so the Halo's bidirectional sensor is a meaningful upgrade.</p>

      <h3>Color Temperature and Tunability</h3>
      <p>The Halo tunes from 2700K (warm candlelight) to 6500K (cool daylight) in 100K steps, with a Color Rendering Index of 95+. That is high enough to do color-accurate work under the bar — we edited photos at night under the Halo set to 5500K and the colors matched our daytime calibration within a Delta E of 1.2.</p>

      <p>For comparison, the Baseus bar offers only three fixed color temperatures (3000K, 4000K, 5500K) with no fine adjustment. The Yeelight Pro offers a 2700K-6500K range but in 500K steps. The Halo's 100K granularity matters if you do visual work; if you only read text, the difference is academic.</p>

      <h3>Build Quality and Mounting</h3>
      <p>The bar itself is matte aluminum with a rubberized clip that fits monitors up to 1.5 inches thick. BenQ includes a separate curved-monitor adapter in the box, which is the difference between the Halo fitting a 1000R Samsung Odyssey and not. The clip has a counterweight that hangs behind the monitor to balance the bar — this is the same mechanism BenQ has used since the original ScreenBar, and it has held up over our 90 days without sagging.</p>

      <p>The bar weighs 1.4 lbs, which is light enough that the monitor does not tilt forward under the load but heavy enough to feel substantial. The knob is milled aluminum with a rubber base. The included USB-C cable is braided and 5 feet long, which is plenty to reach a monitor USB hub or a desktop.</p>

      <h3>USB-C and Power</h3>
      <p>The Halo draws 5V 1A from any USB port. We tested it on a monitor USB hub, a desktop USB-A port, a USB-C phone charger, and a portable battery — all worked without issue. There is no proprietary power brick, which means if you lose the cable any USB-C cable works as a replacement. The original ScreenBar Plus used USB-A only; the Halo's switch to USB-C input is a small but real quality-of-life upgrade.</p>

      <p>For eye care and ergonomics context, pairing the Halo with <a href="/reviews/best-blue-light-glasses/">blue light glasses</a> at night gave us the most comfortable evening work session we have measured. The Halo alone is good; the Halo with eye protection is the gold standard.</p>

      <h2 id="comparison">How It Compares to the Competition</h2>
      <p>We tested four monitor light bars head to head. Here is how the top three stack up:</p>

