      <p>The original ScreenBar Plus remains the value pick. For $30 less you get the same asymmetric optics and a perfectly serviceable in-line dial. What you give up is the wireless knob, the bidirectional auto-dimming, and the 100K color granularity. If you work in a fixed lighting environment and never touch brightness after the first week, save the $30.</p>

      <p>The Yeelight Pro is the middle ground. It matches the Halo on paper for color range but loses on optics — its beam is partially asymmetric, which means a faint reflection on glossy screens. At $69 it is a fine budget pick if you cannot justify the Halo, but we would steer most buyers toward the ScreenBar Plus instead for the same money.</p>

      <p>For a wider field of options, our <a href="/reviews/best-monitor-light-bar/">monitor light bar roundup</a> covers eight bars across every price tier, including picks for travel and dual-monitor setups. If you are building a full ergonomic workstation, the Halo pairs naturally with a <a href="/reviews/best-standing-desk-converter/">standing desk converter</a> so you can adjust both your screen height and your desk lighting in one upgrade cycle.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the Halo if you work at a monitor after sunset more than three nights per week. At that usage the wireless knob and auto-dimming earn back the $30 premium over the ScreenBar Plus within a month of nightly use. If you only occasionally work at night, save the money and buy the ScreenBar Plus — the optics are identical.</p>

      <p>Verify your monitor thickness before ordering. The Halo clip fits up to 1.5 inches thick without the curved adapter and up to 1.8 inches with it. Most modern ultrawides are under 1.2 inches, so this is rarely an issue, but if you have an older thick-edge monitor or a wall-mounted display, measure first.</p>

      <p>Buy from a retailer with a 30-day return window. The Halo's value depends entirely on whether you actually use the wireless knob. If you find yourself leaving it on a fixed brightness after week one, return the Halo and exchange it for the ScreenBar Plus — you will save $30 and lose nothing you were using.</p>

      <p>Finally, plan your power. The Halo needs a USB port within 5 feet of the monitor top. If your monitor has no USB hub and your desktop is on the floor, you will need a USB extension cable or a small USB wall charger. We use a $9 Anker USB-C wall brick and it works perfectly.</p>

